definition.value: A probe that is a small labelled and chemical active peptide which has been structurally modified for reacting with, for example, the beta-lactam moieties of various penicillin-type compounds.

A tetrapeptide comprising in sequence an alpha-aspartyl residue, two lysyl residues and a beta-alanyl residue, to the nitrogen of the aspartyl residue of which are linked both a methyl group and a 7-nitro-2,1,3-benzoxadiazol-4-yl moiety, while the epsilon nitrogen of the lysyl(II) residue carries a biotin moiety. It is used a peptide probe, with the biotin moiety finding application in immunoassays.
A butenolide that is (5-oxo-2,5-dihydrofuran-3-yl)methyl phosphate carrying an additional 6-methylheptanoyl substituent at position 4.

A tripeptide comprising in sequence alpha-aspartyl, lysyl residue and beta-alanyl residues, to the nitrogen of the aspartyl residue of which are linked both a methyl group and a 7-nitro-2,1,3-benzoxadiazol-4-yl moiety.

A dipeptide comprising in sequence alpha-aspartyl and beta-alanyl residues, to the nitrogen of the aspartyl residue of which are linked both a methyl group and a 7-nitro-2,1,3-benzoxadiazol-4-yl moiety.
A tripeptide comprising in sequence glycyl, lysyl and beta-alanyl residues, to the nitrogen of the glycyl residue of which is linked a 2,4-dinitrophenyl moiety.
A polyanionic polymer obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy groups of [8)-alpha-Neu5Ac-(2->]n; major species at pH 7.3.
A retinoid anion that is the conjugate base of 9-cis-4-hydroxyretinoic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
A retinoid anion that is the conjugate base of 9-cis-4-oxoretinoic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
A retinoid that consists of 9-cis-retinoic acid bearing an oxo substituent at position 4 on the cyclohexenyl ring.
A retinoid that consists of all-trans-retinoic acid bearing an hydroxy substituent at position 16.
A retinoid anion that is the conjugate base of all-trans-16-hydroxyretinoic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
A retinoid anion that is the conjugate base of all-trans-18-hydroxyretinoic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
A retinoid that consists of all-trans-retinoic acid bearing two hydroxy substituents at positions 4 and 16.
A retinoid anion that is the conjugate base of all-trans-4,16-dihydroxyretinoic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
A retinoid that consists of all-trans-retinoic acid bearing two hydroxy substituents at positions 4 and 18.
A retinoid anion that is the conjugate base of all-trans-4,18-dihydroxyretinoic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
A retinoid that consists of all-trans-retinoic acid carrying an oxo substituent at position 4 and a hydroxy substituent at position 16.
A retinoid anion that is the conjugate base of all-trans-4-oxo-16-hydroxyretinoic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
A retinoid that consists of all-trans-retinoic acid carrying an oxo substituent at position 4 and a hydroxy substituent at position 18.
A retinoid anion that is the conjugate base of all-trans-4-oxo-18-hydroxyretinoic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
A butan-4-olide that is (5-oxooxolan-3-yl)methyl phosphate carrying an additional 6-methylheptanoyl substituent at position 4.
A 3-hydroxy fatty acyl-CoA resulting from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of (S)-3-hydroxypentanoic acid.

A  C21-steroid that is cortisone bearing an additional hydroxy substituent at the 6beta-position. It is produced as a metabolite of cortisol by cytochrome p450-3A4 (CYP3A4, an important enzyme involved in the metabolism of a variety of exogenous and endogenous compounds) and can be used to detect moderate and potent CYP3A4 inhibition in vivo.
A 3-hydroxypentanoic acid in which the chiral centre at position 3 has S-configuration.

A C21-steroid that is cortisol bearing an additional hydroxy substituent at the 6beta-position. In humans, it is produced as a metabolite of cortisol by cytochrome p450-3A4 (CYP3A4, an important enzyme involved in the metabolism of a variety of exogenous and endogenous compounds) and can be used to detect moderate and potent CYP3A4 inhibition in vivo.
A short-chain fatty acid that is valeric acid in which one of the methylene hydrogens at position 3 has been replaced by a hydroxy group.
A phenolate anion that is the conjugate base of 4-O-methylxanthohumol, obtained by deprotonation of the 1-hydroxy group. It is the major microspecies at pH 7.3 (according to Marvin v 6.2.0.).
A steroid glucuronide anion that is the conjugate base of calcitriol 25-O-(beta-D-glucuronide) arising from deprotonation of the carboxylic acid function; major species at pH 7.3.

A branched tetrasaccharide galactosyl group consisting of alpha-L-fucosyl and two beta-D-galactosyl residues linked sequentially (1->2) and (1->3), to the non-reducing-end galactosyl residue of which is also linked (1->3) an N-acetyl-alpha-D-galactosyl residue. Blood group type-V A determinant.

A branched tetrasaccharide glucosyl group consisting of alpha-L-fucosyl, beta-D-galactosyl and beta-D-glucosyl residues linked sequentially (1->2) and (1->3), to the galactosyl residue of which is also linked (1->3) an N-acetyl-alpha-D-galactosaminyl residue. Blood group type-VI A determinant.
A steroid glucuronide anion that is the conjugate base of calcidiol 25-O-(beta-D-glucuronide) arising from deprotonation of the carboxylic acid function; major species at pH 7.3.
A steroid glucuronide anion that is the conjugate base of calcidiol 3-O-(beta-D-glucuronide) arising from deprotonation of the carboxylic acid function; major species at pH 7.3.

A branched tetrasaccharide galactosyl group consisting of alpha-L-fucosyl and two beta-D-galactosyl residues linked sequentially (1->2) and (1->3), to the non-reducing-end galactosyl residue of which is also linked (1->3) an alpha-D-galactosyl residue. Blood group type-V B determinant.

A branched tetrasaccharide glucosyl group consisting of alpha-L-fucosyl, beta-D-galactosyl and beta-D-glucosyl residues linked sequentially (1->2) and (1->3), to the galactosyl residue of which is also linked (1->3) an alpha-D-galactosyl residue. Blood group type-VI B determinant.
A glycoside formed between the branched tetrasaccharide alpha-L-Fuc-(1->2)-[alpha-D-GalNAc-(1->3)]-beta-D-Gal-(1->3)-beta-D-GlcNAc and the alkenyl alcohol oct-7-en-1-ol.
A polyanionic polymer obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy groups of [(2->8)-N,O(7)-diacetyl-alpha-D-neuraminosyl]n; major species at pH 7.3.
A polyanionic polymer obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy groups of [(2->8)-N,O(9)-diacetyl-alpha-D-neuraminosyl]n; major species at pH 7.3.
A polyanionic polymer obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy groups of [(2->6)-alpha-D-glucosyl-(1->4)-N-acetyl-alpha-D-neuraminosyl]n; major species at pH 7.3.
A polyanionic polymer obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy groups of [(2->6)-alpha-D-glucosyl-(1->4)-N,O(7)-diacetyl-alpha-D-neuraminosyl]n; major species at pH 7.3.
A polyanionic polymer obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy groups of [(2->6)-alpha-D-glucosyl-(1->4)-N,O(9)-diacetyl-alpha-D-neuraminosyl]n; major species at pH 7.3.
A cyclic tetrapyrrole anion that is the carbanion obtained by removal of the acidic proton from position 21 of any chlorophyll. Major species at pH 7.3
A cyclic tetrapyrrole anion obtained by removal of the acidic proton from position 21 as well as deprotonation of the carboxy group of any chlorophyllide. Major species at pH 7.3
A purine ribonucleoside 5'-monophosphate that is adenosine 5'-monophosphate in which one of the hydroxy groups of the phosphate has been condensed with the carboxylic acid group of D-alanine.
